<br>
Here are the important things to consider in my opinion, listed pretty much in the order in which I rate them.<br>
<br>
1) Focus effects. A single critical focus effect is usually worth more than the stats of several items combined. The most important for any caster is mana preservation. Read gravely's text about the spell casting mastery aa for the math, as this applies to mana preservation too. <br>
<br>
The second most important focus effect would be improved healing. The main task of a cleric is to heal, and an extra 1-20% to a quick heal can often save the day.<br>
<br>
Spell haste is handy, but a lot of cleric combat spells aren't affected by spell haste, like supernal remedy, DA, DB, stuns, greater immobilize and complete heal. In fact, post 60 I think the only cleric combat spells affected by spell haste are pacification and supernal light. Having spell haste to cast virtue is certainly handy, but hardly a measure of performance.<br>
<br>
Extended reinforcement may seem interesting, but it doesn't work on the spells you really want extended, like the elixir line, yaulp, and DA/DB. To extend these, you'll need aa pts - and at the present moment that would dramatically reduce your pacification duration.<br>
<br>
<br>
2) Flowing thought: A cleric's mana <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>regeneration</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> - not necessarily mana pool - is often the bottleneck on how effective a group will be, is definitely what's holding back a large amount of raids, and is certainly directly affecting the degree of effectiveness at which you can solo. <br>
<br>
<br>
3) HP vs Mana. This is something you have to decide for yourself. A long time ago on my previous server, I was leveling my little enchanter, and I was dying a lot. As I was painfully going up through the levels I started noticing a disturbing tendency: I was invariably dying with quite a bit of mana left, and very rarely was going oom and getting myself or someone else killed as a consequence. So I started wearing hp gear over int/mana or cha gear. And while the death count went down dramatically, I was still dying with mana left way more often than I was going oom at critical moments. So I kept favoring Hp gear over anything else and until FT gear was released simply never came close to the point where I could consider giving up hp gear for mana gear. This changed with PoP and using charm a lot more and more mana intensive spells, but if I don't have a pet up it's basically the same mechanics and results.<br>
<br>
Now this might not apply entirely to clerics, but from casual observation I see clerics generating a lot of aggro, and I seem to see a lot of clerics dying with tons of mana left . Certainly a lot more than I see calling oom at a critical moment. So my suggestion if that's the case, is first to look in your gameplay habits to see if you could do anything to increase your survivability. And after doing that start trading out wis/mana gear for hp gear, and keep doing that until you get close to a  point where your amount of dying with significant mana left is starting to balance out with the amount time you get oom at a critical moment.<br>
<br>
Also, remember that going out of mana can be the result of attrition over a long period of time, and for that increasing your mana pool by even a large amount will do very little. You'd much better off with investing in FT gear instead in these situations, or even better, mana preservation if you don't have any.<br>
<br>
