<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Complete Healing still generates more healing per second.  Healing AAs apply to complete healing, too (I'm at 8925 base).  Even with IH4, complete healing &gt; supernal light.  I rarely, rarely memorize that spell... because a maxed-AA, IH4 Supernal Remedy is just fine when you need speed (up to 2115 non-crit, 16% chance of crit, maximum of which is 3926).  Supernal Light has one definite good use that Iumuno brought to my attention... suppose you're on a CH chain, and your supernal light runs 3 seconds with full spell haste.  If you're trying to stay out of range of an AE and you hit your CH button and get an out of range message, don't panic... count to 7 as you get in range, then cast supernal light... at least you'll deliver a fairly large heal when your CH would have landed.<br>
<br>
Spell haste is good for a couple other spells, ethereal elixir (but usually that's not time-critical, since it's a heal over time and only does 300/tick for 4 ticks) and Word of Replenishment, and even Word of Restoration (group CH, so you can cut it from 12 to 9 seconds with BoR and 15% item spell haste).<br>
<br>
I agree fully with Iumuno about hitpoints.  I don't believe in AC (at least for clerics) either.  I mean yes, it does something, but my job is not to be an efficient tank.  My job is to keep the group, including myself alive.<br>
<br>
Suppose you have say, roughly 1600 hps and Virtue and BAotR put you at 3300, with 1200 AC.  Now, you're fighting something that triples for 600, and you're medding.  You catch some heal aggro when you next sit, and get tripled for 1800 total, putting you at 1500.  Now, suppose you can't ditch aggro.  What happens if the mob does 83% or more of its max round on the next round of attacks?  You die.  Even if it only does just over 700 damage next round, you're under 25% hps (at 800 out of 3300) and you'll have &quot;blood aggro&quot; or &quot;frenzy aggro&quot; or whatever people call it here on FV.  That forces you to heal yoursel with a fast heal, and creates more aggro.<br>
<br>
Now, if instead you went for hps, got up to say 2300 with only 1000 AC, then buffed you're at 4000.  You get hit sitting and take 1800, putting you at 2200.  Two things have changed.  A max round from the mob <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>cannot kill you</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  In addition, in order to stay above blood aggro level (25% or 1000 hps) you can take up to 1200 damage in the next round, or 66% of its max round without blood aggro.  In this case, the hitpoints are more likely to keep you alive.<br>
<br>
Resists - I agree with Iumuno again.  For efficiency on long fights, sure, they're invaluable.  But really, if you're talking survivability, hitpoints are the only way to guarantee survival.  It's a rare AE that's going to kill you outright, but there are some 3k to 3500 AEs out there.  Here's maybe a good example.  Suppose you are off to kill Trakanon.  He likes to dot you up good.  His AE has like a n300 resist adjust.  To even begin to think about resisting it, you need 400+ poison resists.  Keep in mind, Trak is going to AE more than once, so don't think a fluke resist is enough.  To get halfway reliable resists of the AE you need 450+, and to really consistently resist it, we're talking 500 svp.  Why would you sacrifice hitpoints to try to attain that, though?  Why not just get enough hitpoints so you a) survive the AE, and b) buy more time to cure/heal yourself (raidant cure &gt; all for trak's breath) and c) don't get blood aggro and get summoned and chomped on.<br>
<br>
Another benefit of hitpoints is you increase the effectiveness of Divine Arbitration.  If you add 600 hps to yourself, you add 100 hps to the group's average... that's 100 more hitpoints someone gets when you use Divine Arbitration to save them.  You're effectively adding 100 to your &quot;heal&quot; from that ability.<br>
<br>
Best ways to add hps:<br>
<br>
1) got an item that's 15 wisdom and 25 mana?  Consider replacing it with a good hp item.  Probably your wisdom is plenty high anyway.<br>
<br>
2) ignore AC on items.  Just don't even consider it as a factor.  Many good hp items have good AC anyway, so you won't have a problem with a low AC if you go for hitpoints.<br>
<br>
3) Ignore fire, cold, poison and disease resists on items.  See 2).  You'll get resists anyway in the process, just don't stress about any except MR, and don't stress *too* much about that one, either.<br>
<br>
Focus items &gt; hps.  See Iumuno's post.  Mana Preservation &gt; all.<br>
<br>
I see from your magelo you did SCR2.  Your Pacification duration is already &quot;broken&quot; from the (bugged) 5 minutes, so now there's no reason not to do SCR3 and SCRM.  They should increase duration on heals over time, divine aura/barrier, etc, from what I've been told.  Good stuff. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Natural Durability is a good AA skill... it will add about 300 hps total for me (roughly 60/90/150), but I haven't finished it yet because cleric AAs are generally quite good and there are a ton of things I wanted first. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Well, I wrote enough for now.  Happy shopping! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
