<br>
Lets say an average tank (not talking FnF's top raid tank).. say raid buffed... is going to have what 6500 hitpoints... give or take a few.<br>
<br>
And lets say your average complete heal hits them when they are at 30% (its probably higher, much lower and you risk the tank dying from a flurry)... that means your CH is doing ummm.... 4500 hit points per heal.<br>
<br>
So we can thus theorise that complete heal does 450 hit points per second (10 second cast time).<br>
<br>
Now lets look at supernal (damn forgotten its name already..)...<br>
<br>
With appropriate aa's and focus effects it will produce an easy 3000 hit point heal.<br>
<br>
Given the fast cast focus and revernance it takes what 3 seconds to cast....<br>
<br>
That gives supernal remedy 1000 hit points per second.<br>
<br>
So in summary,<br>
<br>
Complete heal 450 hps<br>
Supernal remedy 1000hps<br>
<br>
Clearly supernal remedy is the vastly superior spell when you have an &quot;average&quot; tank. If you tank has like 10000 hit points raid buffed the results are clearly different and will begin to favour CH more and more..<br>
<br>
Clearly this doesnt take into account mana effeciency etc etc, It just shows that for high dps mobs you have a healing spell that has the high hps to counter with.<br>
